Conington, who in his first edition says ‘that Virgil clearly refers specially to Lucretius', in his second seems to come to much the same conclusion as I had come to. But now, when I compare geor. 11 475— 482, 111 which Virgil expresses his longing to be the poet 01 science, with 490—492 Felix qui cet. 3 and then 483-489, in which he declares that, 11 his genius is unequal to that, he will seek the country and its enjoy- ments, with 493 494 Fortunatus et ille oet, I feel that by his Felix qui Virgil does mean a poet-philosopher, who can only be Lueretius.
